# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: meltdown-mitigation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] A **central processing unit** (**CPU**), also known as a **central processor**, **main processor**, or simply **processor**, is the primary processor in a given computer.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Its electronic circuitry executes instructions of a computer program, such as arithmetic, logic, controlling, and input/output (I/O) operations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] This role contrasts with that of external components, such as main memory and I/O circuitry, and specialized coprocessors such as graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The form, design, and implementation of CPUs have changed over time, but their fundamental operation remains almost unchanged.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Modern CPUs devote a lot of semiconductor area to caches and instruction-level parallelism to increase performance and to CPU modes to support operating systems and virtualization.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Most modern CPUs are implemented on integrated circuit (IC) microprocessors, with one or more CPUs on a single IC chip.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Microprocessor chips with multiple CPUs are called *multi-core processors* (*MCPs*).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The individual physical CPUs, called *processor cores*, can also be multithreaded to support CPU-level multithreading.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] An IC that contains a CPU may also contain memory, peripheral interfaces, and other components of a computer; such integrated devices are variously called microcontrollers or systems on chip (SoCs).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Early computers such as the ENIAC had to be physically rewired to perform different tasks, which caused these machines to be called "fixed-program computers".
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The "central processing unit" term has been in use since as early as 1955.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Since the term "CPU" is generally defined as a device for software (computer program) execution, the earliest devices that could rightly be called CPUs came with the advent of the stored-program computer.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The idea of a stored-program computer had already been present in the design of John Presper Eckert and John William Mauchly's ENIAC, but was initially omitted so that it could be finished sooner.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] On June 30, 1945, before ENIAC was made, mathematician John von Neumann distributed a paper entitled *First Draft of a Report on the EDVAC*.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] It was the outline of a stored-program computer that would eventually be completed in August 1949.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] EDVAC was designed to perform a certain number of instructions (or operations) of various types.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Significantly, the programs written for EDVAC were to be stored in high-speed computer memory rather than specified by the physical wiring of the computer.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] This overcame a severe limitation of ENIAC, which was the considerable time and effort required to reconfigure the computer to perform a new task.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] With von Neumann's design, the program that EDVAC ran could be changed simply by changing the contents of the memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] EDVAC was not the first stored-program computer; the Manchester Baby, which was a small-scale experimental stored-program computer, ran its first program on 21 June 1948 and the Manchester Mark 1 ran its first program during the night of 16–17 June 1949.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Early CPUs were custom designs used as part of a larger and sometimes distinctive computer.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] However, this method of designing custom CPUs for a particular application has largely given way to the development of multi-purpose processors produced in large quantities.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] This standardization began in the era of discrete transistor mainframes and minicomputers, and has rapidly accelerated with the popularization of the integrated circuit (IC).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The IC has allowed increasingly complex CPUs to be designed and manufactured to tolerances on the order of nanometers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Both the miniaturization and standardization of CPUs have increased the presence of digital devices in modern life far beyond the limited application of dedicated computing machines.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Modern microprocessors appear in electronic devices ranging from automobiles to cellphones, and sometimes even in toys.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] While von Neumann is most often credited with the design of the stored-program computer because of his design of EDVAC, and the design became known as the von Neumann architecture, others before him, such as Konrad Zuse, had suggested and implemented similar ideas.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The so-called Harvard architecture of the Harvard Mark I, which was completed before EDVAC, also used a stored-program design using punched paper tape rather than electronic memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The key difference between the two is that Harvard architecture separates the storage and treatment of CPU instructions and data, whereas von Neumann architecture uses the same memory space for both.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Most modern CPUs are primarily von Neumann in design, but CPUs with the Harvard architecture are seen as well, especially in embedded applications; for instance, the Atmel AVR microcontrollers are Harvard-architecture processors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Prior to the invention of the transistor, relays and vacuum tubes (thermionic tubes) were commonly used as switching elements; a useful computer requires thousands or tens of thousands of switching devices.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The overall speed of a system is dependent on the speed of the switches.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Vacuum-tube computers such as EDVAC tended to average eight hours between failures, whereas relay computers—such as the slower but earlier Harvard Mark I—failed very rarely.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In the end, tube-based CPUs became dominant because the significant speed advantages afforded generally outweighed the reliability problems.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Most of these early synchronous CPUs ran at low clock rates compared to modern microelectronic designs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Clock signal frequencies ranging from 100 kHz to 4 MHz were very common at this time, limited largely by the speed of the switching devices they were built with.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The design complexity of CPUs increased as various technologies facilitated the building of smaller and more reliable electronic devices.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The first such improvement came with the advent of the transistor.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Transistorized CPUs during the 1950s and 1960s no longer had to be built out of bulky, unreliable, and fragile switching elements, like vacuum tubes and relays.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] With this improvement, more complex and reliable CPUs were built onto one or several printed circuit boards containing discrete (individual) components.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In 1964, IBM introduced its IBM System/360 computer architecture that was used in a series of computers capable of running the same programs with different speeds and performances.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] This was significant at a time when most electronic computers were incompatible with one another, even those made by the same manufacturer.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] To facilitate this improvement, IBM used the concept of a microprogram (often called "microcode"), which still sees widespread use in modern CPUs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The System/360 architecture was so popular that it dominated the mainframe computer market for decades and left a legacy that is continued by similar modern computers like the IBM zSeries.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In 1965, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) introduced another influential computer aimed at the scientific and research markets—the PDP-8.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Transistor-based computers had several distinct advantages over their predecessors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Aside from facilitating increased reliability and lower power consumption, transistors also allowed CPUs to operate at much higher speeds because of the short switching time of a transistor in comparison to a tube or relay.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The increased reliability and dramatically increased speed of the switching elements, which were almost exclusively transistors by this time; CPU clock rates in the tens of megahertz were easily obtained during this period.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Additionally, while discrete transistor and IC CPUs were in heavy usage, new high-performance designs like single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) vector processors began to appear.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] These early experimental designs later gave rise to the era of specialized supercomputers like those made by Cray Inc and Fujitsu Ltd.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] During this period, a method of manufacturing many interconnected transistors in a compact space was developed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The integrated circuit (IC) allowed a large number of transistors to be manufactured on a single semiconductor-based die, or "chip".
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] At first, only very basic non-specialized digital circuits such as NOR gates were miniaturized into ICs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] CPUs based on these "building block" ICs are generally referred to as "small-scale integration" (SSI) devices.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] SSI ICs, such as the ones used in the Apollo Guidance Computer, usually contained up to a few dozen transistors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] To build an entire CPU out of SSI ICs required thousands of individual chips, but still consumed much less space and power than earlier discrete transistor designs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] IBM's System/370, follow-on to the System/360, used SSI ICs rather than Solid Logic Technology discrete-transistor modules.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] DEC's PDP-8/I and KI10 PDP-10 also switched from the individual transistors used by the PDP-8 and KA PDP-10 to SSI ICs, and their extremely popular PDP-11 line was originally built with SSI ICs, but was eventually implemented with LSI components once these became practical.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Lee Boysel published influential articles, including a 1967 "manifesto", which described how to build the equivalent of a 32-bit mainframe computer from a relatively small number of large-scale integration circuits (LSI).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The only way to build LSI chips, which are chips with a hundred or more gates, was to build them using a metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) semiconductor manufacturing process (either PMOS logic, NMOS logic, or CMOS logic).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] However, some companies continued to build processors out of bipolar transistor–transistor logic (TTL) chips because bipolar junction transistors were faster than MOS chips up until the 1970s (a few companies such as Datapoint continued to build processors out of TTL chips until the early 1980s).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In the 1960s, MOS ICs were slower and initially considered useful only in applications that required low power.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Following the development of silicon-gate MOS technology by Federico Faggin at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1968, MOS ICs largely replaced bipolar TTL as the standard chip technology in the late 1970s.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] As the microelectronic technology advanced, an increasing number of transistors were placed on ICs, decreasing the number of individual ICs needed for a complete CPU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] MSI and LSI ICs increased transistor counts to hundreds, and then thousands.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] By 1968, the number of ICs required to build a complete CPU had been reduced to 24 ICs of eight different types, with each IC containing roughly 1000 MOSFETs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In stark contrast with its SSI and MSI predecessors, the first LSI implementation of the PDP-11 contained a CPU composed of only four LSI integrated circuits.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Since microprocessors were first introduced they have almost completely overtaken all other central processing unit implementation methods.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The first commercially available microprocessor, made in 1971, was the Intel 4004.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The Intel 4004 was one of the first consumer-facing CPUs integrating arithmetic logic unit, control unit, and register unit on a chip.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The first widely used microprocessor, made in 1974, was the Intel 8080.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Mainframe and minicomputer manufacturers of the time launched proprietary IC development programs to upgrade their older computer architectures, and eventually produced instruction set compatible microprocessors that were backward-compatible with their older hardware and software.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Combined with the advent and eventual success of the ubiquitous personal computer, the term *CPU* is now applied almost exclusively to microprocessors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Several CPUs (denoted *cores*) can be combined in a single processing chip.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Previous generations of CPUs were implemented as discrete components and numerous small integrated circuits (ICs) on one or more circuit boards.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Microprocessors, on the other hand, are CPUs manufactured on a very small number of ICs; usually just one.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The overall smaller CPU size, as a result of being implemented on a single die, means faster switching time because of physical factors like decreased gate parasitic capacitance.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] This has allowed synchronous microprocessors to have clock rates ranging from tens of megahertz to several gigahertz.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Additionally, the ability to construct exceedingly small transistors on an IC has increased the complexity and number of transistors in a single CPU many fold.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] This widely observed trend is described by Moore's law, which had proven to be a fairly accurate predictor of the growth of CPU (and other IC) complexity until 2016.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] While the complexity, size, construction and general form of CPUs have changed enormously since 1950, the basic design and function has not changed much at all.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Almost all common CPUs today can be very accurately described as von Neumann stored-program machines.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] As Moore's law no longer holds, concerns have arisen about the limits of integrated circuit transistor technology.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Extreme miniaturization of electronic gates is causing the effects of phenomena like electromigration and subthreshold leakage to become much more significant.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] These newer concerns are among the many factors causing researchers to investigate new methods of computing such as the quantum computer, as well as to expand the use of parallelism and other methods that extend the usefulness of the classical von Neumann model.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The fundamental operation of most CPUs, regardless of the physical form they take, is to execute a sequence of stored instructions that is called a program.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The instructions to be executed are kept in some kind of computer memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Nearly all CPUs follow the fetch, decode and execute steps in their operation, which are collectively known as the instruction cycle.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] After the execution of an instruction, the entire process repeats, with the next instruction cycle normally fetching the next-in-sequence instruction because of the incremented value in the program counter.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] If a jump instruction was executed, the program counter will be modified to contain the address of the instruction that was jumped to and program execution continues normally.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In more complex CPUs, multiple instructions can be fetched, decoded and executed simultaneously.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] This section describes what is generally referred to as the "classic RISC pipeline", which is quite common among the simple CPUs used in many electronic devices (often called microcontrollers).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] It largely ignores the important role of CPU cache, and therefore the access stage of the pipeline.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Some instructions manipulate the program counter rather than producing result data directly; such instructions are generally called "jumps" and facilitate program behavior like loops, conditional program execution (through the use of a conditional jump), and existence of functions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In some processors, some other instructions change the state of bits in a "flags" register.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] These flags can be used to influence how a program behaves, since they often indicate the outcome of various operations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] For example, in such processors a "compare" instruction evaluates two values and sets or clears bits in the flags register to indicate which one is greater or whether they are equal; one of these flags could then be used by a later jump instruction to determine program flow.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Fetch involves retrieving an instruction (which is represented by a number or sequence of numbers) from program memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The instruction's location (address) in program memory is determined by the program counter (PC; called the "instruction pointer" in Intel x86 microprocessors), which stores a number that identifies the address of the next instruction to be fetched.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] After an instruction is fetched, the PC is incremented by the length of the instruction so that it will contain the address of the next instruction in the sequence.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Often, the instruction to be fetched must be retrieved from relatively slow memory, causing the CPU to stall while waiting for the instruction to be returned.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] This issue is largely addressed in modern processors by caches and pipeline architectures (see below).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The instruction that the CPU fetches from memory determines what the CPU will do.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In the decode step, performed by binary decoder circuitry known as the *instruction decoder*, the instruction is converted into signals that control other parts of the CPU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The way in which the instruction is interpreted is defined by the CPU's instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Often, one group of bits (that is, a "field") within the instruction, called the opcode, indicates which operation is to be performed, while the remaining fields usually provide supplemental information required for the operation, such as the operands.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Those operands may be specified as a constant value (called an immediate value), or as the location of a value that may be a processor register or a memory address, as determined by some addressing mode.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In some CPU designs, the instruction decoder is implemented as a hardwired, unchangeable binary decoder circuit.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In others, a microprogram is used to translate instructions into sets of CPU configuration signals that are applied sequentially over multiple clock pulses.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In some cases the memory that stores the microprogram is rewritable, making it possible to change the way in which the CPU decodes instructions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] After the fetch and decode steps, the execute step is performed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Depending on the CPU architecture, this may consist of a single action or a sequence of actions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] During each action, control signals electrically enable or disable various parts of the CPU so they can perform all or part of the desired operation.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] The action is then completed, typically in response to a clock pulse.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] Very often the results are written to an internal CPU register for quick access by subsequent instructions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] In other cases results may be written to slower, but less expensive and higher capacity main memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] For example, if an instruction that performs addition is to be executed, registers containing operands (numbers to be summed) are activated, as are the parts of the arithmetic logic unit (ALU) that perform addition.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] When the clock pulse occurs, the operands flow from the source registers into the ALU, and the sum appears at its output.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] On subsequent clock pulses, other components are enabled (and disabled) to move the output (the sum of the operation) to storage (e.g., a register or memory).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p01] If the resulting sum is too large (i.e., it is larger than the ALU's output word size), an arithmetic overflow flag will be set, influencing the next operation.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Hardwired into a CPU's circuitry is a set of basic operations it can perform, called an instruction set.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Such operations may involve, for example, adding or subtracting two numbers, comparing two numbers, or jumping to a different part of a program.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Each instruction is represented by a unique combination of bits, known as the machine language opcode.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] While processing an instruction, the CPU decodes the opcode (via a binary decoder) into control signals, which orchestrate the behavior of the CPU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] A complete machine language instruction consists of an opcode and, in many cases, additional bits that specify arguments for the operation (for example, the numbers to be summed in the case of an addition operation).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Going up the complexity scale, a machine language program is a collection of machine language instructions that the CPU executes.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The actual mathematical operation for each instruction is performed by a combinational logic circuit within the CPU's processor known as the arithmetic–logic unit or ALU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In general, a CPU executes an instruction by fetching it from memory, using its ALU to perform an operation, and then storing the result to memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The control unit (CU) is a component of the CPU that directs the operation of the processor.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] It tells the computer's memory, arithmetic and logic unit and input and output devices how to respond to the instructions that have been sent to the processor.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] It directs the operation of the other units by providing timing and control signals.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Most computer resources are managed by the CU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] It directs the flow of data between the CPU and the other devices.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] John von Neumann included the control unit as part of the von Neumann architecture.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In modern computer designs, the control unit is typically an internal part of the CPU with its overall role and operation unchanged since its introduction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The arithmetic logic unit (ALU) is a digital circuit within the processor that performs integer arithmetic and bitwise logic operations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The inputs to the ALU are the data words to be operated on (called operands), status information from previous operations, and a code from the control unit indicating which operation to perform.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Depending on the instruction being executed, the operands may come from internal CPU registers, external memory, or constants generated by the ALU itself.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] When all input signals have settled and propagated through the ALU circuitry, the result of the performed operation appears at the ALU's outputs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The result consists of both a data word, which may be stored in a register or memory, and status information that is typically stored in a special, internal CPU register reserved for this purpose.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Modern CPUs typically contain more than one ALU to improve performance.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The address generation unit (AGU), sometimes also called the address computation unit (ACU), is an execution unit inside the CPU that calculates addresses used by the CPU to access main memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] By having address calculations handled by separate circuitry that operates in parallel with the rest of the CPU, the number of CPU cycles required for executing various machine instructions can be reduced, bringing performance improvements.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] While performing various operations, CPUs need to calculate memory addresses required for fetching data from the memory; for example, in-memory positions of array elements must be calculated before the CPU can fetch the data from actual memory locations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Those address-generation calculations involve different integer arithmetic operations, such as addition, subtraction, modulo operations, or bit shifts.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Often, calculating a memory address involves more than one general-purpose machine instruction, which do not necessarily decode and execute quickly.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] By incorporating an AGU into a CPU design, together with introducing specialized instructions that use the AGU, various address-generation calculations can be offloaded from the rest of the CPU, and can often be executed quickly in a single CPU cycle.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Capabilities of an AGU depend on a particular CPU and its architecture.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Thus, some AGUs implement and expose more address-calculation operations, while some also include more advanced specialized instructions that can operate on multiple operands at a time.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Some CPU architectures include multiple AGUs so more than one address-calculation operation can be executed simultaneously, which brings further performance improvements due to the superscalar nature of advanced CPU designs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, Intel incorporates multiple AGUs into its Sandy Bridge and Haswell microarchitectures, which increase bandwidth of the CPU memory subsystem by allowing multiple memory-access instructions to be executed in parallel.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Many microprocessors (in smartphones and desktop, laptop, server computers) have a memory management unit (MMU), translating logical addresses into physical RAM addresses, providing memory protection and paging abilities, useful for virtual memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The MMU is usually integrated in the processor but in some cases it is in a separate integrated circuit (IC).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Simpler processors, especially microcontrollers, usually do not include an MMU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] A CPU cache is a memory used by the central processing unit (CPU) of a computer to reduce the average cost (time or energy) to access data from the main memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] A cache is a smaller, faster memory, closer to a processor core, which stores copies of the data from frequently used main memory locations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Most CPUs have different independent caches, usually organized as a hierarchy of several cache levels (L1, L2, L3, L4, etc.).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Each ascending cache level is typically slower but larger than the preceding level with L1 being the fastest and the closest to the CPU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] At the L1 level there are usually separate instruction and data caches.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Most modern (fast) CPUs (with few specialized exceptions) have multiple levels of CPU caches.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The first CPUs that used a cache had only one level of cache; unlike later level 1 caches, it was not split into L1d (for data) and L1i (for instructions).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Almost all current CPUs with caches have a split L1 cache.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] They also have L2 caches and, for larger processors, L3 caches as well.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The L2 cache is usually not split and acts as a common repository for the already split L1 cache.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Every core of a multi-core processor has a dedicated L2 cache and is usually not shared between the cores.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The L3 cache, and higher-level caches, are shared between the cores and are not split.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] An L4 cache is currently uncommon, and is generally on dynamic random-access memory (DRAM), rather than on static random-access memory (SRAM), on a separate die or chip.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] That was also the case historically with L1, while bigger chips have allowed integration of it and generally all cache levels, with the possible exception of the last level.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Each extra level of cache tends to be bigger and is optimized differently.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Other types of caches exist (that are not counted towards the "cache size" of the most important caches mentioned above), such as the translation lookaside buffer (TLB) that is part of the memory management unit (MMU) that most CPUs have.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Caches are generally sized in powers of two: 2, 8, 16 etc.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] KiB or MiB (for larger non-L1) sizes, although the IBM z13 has a 96 KiB L1 instruction cache.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Most CPUs are synchronous circuits, which means they employ a clock signal to pace their sequential operations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The clock signal is produced by an external oscillator circuit that generates a consistent number of pulses each second in the form of a periodic square wave.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The frequency of the clock pulses determines the rate at which a CPU executes instructions and, consequently, the faster the clock, the more instructions the CPU will execute each second.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] To ensure proper operation of the CPU, the clock period is longer than the maximum time needed for all signals to propagate (move) through the CPU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In setting the clock period to a value well above the worst-case propagation delay, it is possible to design the entire CPU and the way it moves data around the "edges" of the rising and falling clock signal.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This has the advantage of simplifying the CPU significantly, both from a design perspective and a component-count perspective.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] However, it also carries the disadvantage that the entire CPU must wait on its slowest elements, even though some portions of it are much faster.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This limitation has largely been compensated for by various methods of increasing CPU parallelism (see below).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] However, architectural improvements alone do not solve all of the drawbacks of globally synchronous CPUs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, a clock signal is subject to the delays of any other electrical signal.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Higher clock rates in increasingly complex CPUs make it more difficult to keep the clock signal in phase (synchronized) throughout the entire unit.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This has led many modern CPUs to require multiple identical clock signals to be provided to avoid delaying a single signal significantly enough to cause the CPU to malfunction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Another major issue, as clock rates increase dramatically, is the amount of heat that is dissipated by the CPU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The constantly changing clock causes many components to switch regardless of whether they are being used at that time.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In general, a component that is switching uses more energy than an element in a static state.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Therefore, as clock rate increases, so does energy consumption, causing the CPU to require more heat dissipation in the form of CPU cooling solutions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] One method of dealing with the switching of unneeded components is called clock gating, which involves turning off the clock signal to unneeded components (effectively disabling them).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] However, this is often regarded as difficult to implement and therefore does not see common usage outside of very low-power designs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] One notable CPU design that uses extensive clock gating is the IBM PowerPC-based Xenon used in the Xbox 360; this reduces the power requirements of the Xbox 360.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Another method of addressing some of the problems with a global clock signal is the removal of the clock signal altogether.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] While removing the global clock signal makes the design process considerably more complex in many ways, asynchronous (or clockless) designs carry marked advantages in power consumption and heat dissipation in comparison with similar synchronous designs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] While somewhat uncommon, entire asynchronous CPUs have been built without using a global clock signal.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Two notable examples of this are the ARM compliant AMULET and the MIPS R3000 compatible MiniMIPS.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Rather than totally removing the clock signal, some CPU designs allow certain portions of the device to be asynchronous, such as using asynchronous ALUs in conjunction with superscalar pipelining to achieve some arithmetic performance gains.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] While it is not altogether clear whether totally asynchronous designs can perform at a comparable or better level than their synchronous counterparts, it is evident that they do at least excel in simpler math operations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This, combined with their excellent power consumption and heat dissipation properties, makes them very suitable for embedded computers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Many modern CPUs have a die-integrated power managing module which regulates on-demand voltage supply to the CPU circuitry allowing it to keep balance between performance and power consumption.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Every CPU represents numerical values in a specific way.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, some early digital computers represented numbers as familiar decimal (base 10) numeral system values, and others have employed more unusual representations such as bi-quinary coded decimal (base 2–5) or ternary (base 3).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Nearly all modern CPUs represent numbers in binary form, with each digit being represented by some two-valued physical quantity such as a "high" or "low" voltage.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Related to numeric representation is the size and precision of integer numbers that a CPU can represent.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In the case of a binary CPU, this is measured by the number of bits (significant digits of a binary encoded integer) that the CPU can process in one operation, which is commonly called *word size*, *bit width*, *data path width*, *integer precision*, or *integer size*.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] A CPU's integer size determines the range of integer values on which it can directly operate.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, an 8-bit CPU can directly manipulate integers represented by eight bits, which have a range of 256 (28) discrete integer values.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Integer range can also affect the number of memory locations the CPU can directly address (an address is an integer value representing a specific memory location).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, if a binary CPU uses 32 bits to represent a memory address then it can directly address 232 memory locations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] To circumvent this limitation and for various other reasons, some CPUs use mechanisms (such as memory management or bank switching) that allow additional memory to be addressed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] CPUs with larger word sizes require more circuitry and consequently are physically larger, cost more and consume more power (and therefore generate more heat).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] As a result, smaller 4- or 8-bit microcontrollers are commonly used in modern applications even though CPUs with much larger word sizes (such as 16, 32, 64, even 128-bit) are available.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] When higher performance is required, however, the benefits of a larger word size (larger data ranges and address spaces) may outweigh the disadvantages.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] A CPU can have internal data paths shorter than the word size to reduce size and cost.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] To gain some of the advantages afforded by both lower and higher bit lengths, many instruction sets have different bit widths for integer and floating-point data, allowing CPUs implementing that instruction set to have different bit widths for different portions of the device.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, the IBM System/360 instruction set was primarily 32 bit, but supported 64-bit floating-point values to facilitate greater accuracy and range in floating-point numbers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The System/360 Model 65 had an 8-bit adder for decimal and fixed-point binary arithmetic and a 60-bit adder for floating-point arithmetic.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Many later CPU designs use similar mixed bit width, especially when the processor is meant for general-purpose use where a reasonable balance of integer and floating-point capability is required.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The description of the basic operation of a CPU offered in the previous section describes the simplest form that a CPU can take.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This type of CPU, usually referred to as *subscalar*, operates on and executes one instruction on one or two pieces of data at a time, that is less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This process gives rise to an inherent inefficiency in subscalar CPUs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Since only one instruction is executed at a time, the entire CPU must wait for that instruction to complete before proceeding to the next instruction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] As a result, the subscalar CPU gets "hung up" on instructions which take more than one clock cycle to complete execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Even adding a second execution unit (see below) does not improve performance much; rather than one pathway being hung up, now two pathways are hung up and the number of unused transistors is increased.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This design, wherein the CPU's execution resources can operate on only one instruction at a time, can only possibly reach *scalar* performance (one instruction per clock cycle, IPC = 1).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] However, the performance is nearly always subscalar (less than one instruction per clock cycle, IPC < 1).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Attempts to achieve scalar and better performance have resulted in a variety of design methodologies that cause the CPU to behave less linearly and more in parallel.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Each methodology differs both in the ways in which they are implemented, as well as the relative effectiveness they afford in increasing the CPU's performance for an application.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] One of the simplest methods for increased parallelism is to begin the first steps of instruction fetching and decoding before the prior instruction finishes executing.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This is a technique known as instruction pipelining, and is used in almost all modern general-purpose CPUs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Pipelining allows multiple instructions to be executed at a time by breaking the execution pathway into discrete stages.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This separation can be compared to an assembly line, in which an instruction is made more complete at each stage until it exits the execution pipeline and is retired.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Pipelining does, however, introduce the possibility for a situation where the result of the previous operation is needed to complete the next operation; a condition often termed data dependency conflict.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Therefore, pipelined processors must check for these sorts of conditions and delay a portion of the pipeline if necessary.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] A pipelined processor can become very nearly scalar, inhibited only by pipeline stalls (an instruction spending more than one clock cycle in a stage).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Improvements in instruction pipelining led to further decreases in the idle time of CPU components.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Designs that are said to be superscalar include a long instruction pipeline and multiple identical execution units, such as load–store units, arithmetic–logic units, floating-point units and address generation units.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In a superscalar pipeline, instructions are read and passed to a dispatcher, which decides whether or not the instructions can be executed in parallel (simultaneously).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] If so, they are dispatched to execution units, resulting in their simultaneous execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In general, the number of instructions that a superscalar CPU will complete in a cycle is dependent on the number of instructions it is able to dispatch simultaneously to execution units.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Most of the difficulty in the design of a superscalar CPU architecture lies in creating an effective dispatcher.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The dispatcher needs to be able to quickly determine whether instructions can be executed in parallel, as well as dispatch them in such a way as to keep as many execution units busy as possible.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This requires that the instruction pipeline is filled as often as possible and requires significant amounts of CPU cache.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] It also makes hazard-avoiding techniques like branch prediction, speculative execution, register renaming, out-of-order execution and transactional memory crucial to maintaining high levels of performance.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] By attempting to predict which branch (or path) a conditional instruction will take, the CPU can minimize the number of times that the entire pipeline must wait until a conditional instruction is completed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Speculative execution often provides modest performance increases by executing portions of code that may not be needed after a conditional operation completes.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Out-of-order execution somewhat rearranges the order in which instructions are executed to reduce delays due to data dependencies.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] When a fraction of the CPU is superscalar, the part that is not suffers a performance penalty due to scheduling stalls.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The Intel P5 Pentium had two superscalar ALUs which could accept one instruction per clock cycle each, but its FPU could not.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Thus the P5 was integer superscalar but not floating point superscalar.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Intel's successor to the P5 architecture, P6, added superscalar abilities to its floating-point features.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Simple pipelining and superscalar design increase a CPU's ILP by allowing it to execute instructions at rates surpassing one instruction per clock cycle.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Most modern CPU designs are at least somewhat superscalar, and nearly all general purpose CPUs designed in the last decade are superscalar.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In later years some of the emphasis in designing high-ILP computers has been moved out of the CPU's hardware and into its software interface, or instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The strategy of the very long instruction word (VLIW) causes some ILP to become implied directly by the software, reducing the CPU's work in boosting ILP and thereby reducing design complexity.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Another strategy of achieving performance is to execute multiple threads or processes in parallel.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This area of research is known as parallel computing.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In Flynn's taxonomy, this strategy is known as multiple instruction stream, multiple data stream (MIMD).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] One technology used for this purpose is multiprocessing (MP).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The initial type of this technology is known as symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), where a small number of CPUs share a coherent view of their memory system.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In this scheme, each CPU has additional hardware to maintain a constantly up-to-date view of memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] By avoiding stale views of memory, the CPUs can cooperate on the same program and programs can migrate from one CPU to another.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] To increase the number of cooperating CPUs beyond a handful, schemes such as non-uniform memory access (NUMA) and directory-based coherence protocols were introduced in the 1990s.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] SMP systems are limited to a small number of CPUs while NUMA systems have been built with thousands of processors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Initially, multiprocessing was built using multiple discrete CPUs and boards to implement the interconnect between the processors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] When the processors and their interconnect are all implemented on a single chip, the technology is known as chip-level multiprocessing (CMP) and the single chip as a multi-core processor.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] It was later recognized that finer-grain parallelism existed with a single program.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] A single program might have several threads (or functions) that could be executed separately or in parallel.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Some of the earliest examples of this technology implemented input/output processing such as direct memory access as a separate thread from the computation thread.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] A more general approach to this technology was introduced in the 1970s when systems were designed to run multiple computation threads in parallel.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This technology is known as multi-threading (MT).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The approach is considered more cost-effective than multiprocessing, as only a small number of components within a CPU are replicated to support MT as opposed to the entire CPU in the case of MP.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In MT, the execution units and the memory system including the caches are shared among multiple threads.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The downside of MT is that the hardware support for multithreading is more visible to software than that of MP and thus supervisor software like operating systems have to undergo larger changes to support MT.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] One type of MT that was implemented is known as temporal multithreading, where one thread is executed until it is stalled waiting for data to return from external memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In this scheme, the CPU would then quickly context switch to another thread which is ready to run, the switch often done in one CPU clock cycle, such as the UltraSPARC T1.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Another type of MT is simultaneous multithreading, where instructions from multiple threads are executed in parallel within one CPU clock cycle.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] For several decades from the 1970s to early 2000s, the focus in designing high performance general purpose CPUs was largely on achieving high ILP through technologies such as pipelining, caches, superscalar execution, out-of-order execution, etc.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This trend culminated in large, power-hungry CPUs such as the Intel Pentium 4.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] By the early 2000s, CPU designers were thwarted from achieving higher performance from ILP techniques due to the growing disparity between CPU operating frequencies and main memory operating frequencies as well as escalating CPU power dissipation owing to more esoteric ILP techniques.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] CPU designers then borrowed ideas from commercial computing markets such as transaction processing, where the aggregate performance of multiple programs, also known as throughput computing, was more important than the performance of a single thread or process.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This reversal of emphasis is evidenced by the proliferation of dual and more core processor designs and notably, Intel's newer designs resembling its less superscalar P6 architecture.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] A less common but increasingly important paradigm of processors (and indeed, computing in general) deals with data parallelism.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The processors discussed earlier are all referred to as some type of scalar device.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] As the name implies, vector processors deal with multiple pieces of data in the context of one instruction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This contrasts with scalar processors, which deal with one piece of data for every instruction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Using Flynn's taxonomy, these two schemes of dealing with data are generally referred to as *single instruction* stream, *multiple data* stream (SIMD) and *single instruction* stream, *single data* stream (SISD), respectively.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The great utility in creating processors that deal with vectors of data lies in optimizing tasks that tend to require the same operation (for example, a sum or a dot product) to be performed on a large set of data.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Some classic examples of these types of tasks include multimedia applications (images, video and sound), as well as many types of scientific and engineering tasks.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Whereas a scalar processor must complete the entire process of fetching, decoding and executing each instruction and value in a set of data, a vector processor can perform a single operation on a comparatively large set of data with one instruction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This is only possible when the application tends to require many steps which apply one operation to a large set of data.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Most early vector processors, such as the Cray-1, were associated almost exclusively with scientific research and cryptography applications.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] However, as multimedia has largely shifted to digital media, the need for some form of SIMD in general-purpose processors has become significant.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Shortly after inclusion of floating-point units started to become commonplace in general-purpose processors, specifications for and implementations of SIMD execution units also began to appear for general-purpose processors in the mid-1990s.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Some of these early SIMD specifications – like HP's Multimedia Acceleration eXtensions (MAX) and Intel's MMX – were integer-only.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This proved to be a significant impediment for some software developers, since many of the applications that benefit from SIMD primarily deal with floating-point numbers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Progressively, developers refined and remade these early designs into some of the common modern SIMD specifications, which are usually associated with one instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Some notable modern examples include Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE) and the PowerPC-related AltiVec (also known as VMX).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Many modern architectures (including embedded ones) often include hardware performance counters (HPC), which enables low-level (instruction-level) collection, benchmarking, debugging or analysis of running software metrics.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] HPC may also be used to discover and analyze unusual or suspicious activity of the software, such as return-oriented programming (ROP) or sigreturn-oriented programming (SROP) exploits etc.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This is usually done by software-security teams to assess and find malicious binary programs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Many major vendors (such as IBM, Intel, AMD, and Arm) provide software interfaces (usually written in C/C++) that can be used to collect data from the CPU's registers in order to get metrics.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Operating system vendors also provide software like `perf` (Linux) to record, benchmark, or trace CPU events running kernels and applications.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Hardware counters provide a low-overhead method for collecting comprehensive performance metrics related to a CPU's core elements (functional units, caches, main memory, etc.) – a significant advantage over software profilers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Additionally, they generally eliminate the need to modify the underlying source code of a program.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Because hardware designs differ between architectures, the specific types and interpretations of hardware counters will also change.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Most modern CPUs have privileged modes to support operating systems and virtualization.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Cloud computing can use virtualization to provide a **virtual central processing unit** (**vCPU**) for separate users; vCPU is not to be confused with a virtual private server (VPS).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] A host is the virtual equivalent of a physical machine, on which a virtual system is operating.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] When there are several physical machines operating in tandem and managed as a whole, the grouped computing and memory resources form a cluster.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In some systems, it is possible to dynamically add and remove from a cluster.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Resources available at a host and cluster level can be partitioned into resources pools with fine granularity.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The *performance* or *speed* of a processor depends on, among many other factors, the clock rate (generally given in multiples of hertz) and the instructions per clock (IPC), which together are the factors for the instructions per second (IPS) that the CPU can perform.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Many reported IPS values have represented "peak" execution rates on artificial instruction sequences with few branches, whereas realistic workloads consist of a mix of instructions and applications, some of which take longer to execute than others.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] The performance of the memory hierarchy also greatly affects processor performance, an issue barely considered in IPS calculations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Because of these problems, various standardized tests, often called "benchmarks" for this purpose – such as SPECint – have been developed to attempt to measure the real effective performance in commonly used applications.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Processing performance of computers is increased by using multi-core processors, which essentially is plugging two or more individual processors (called *cores* in this sense) into one integrated circuit.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Ideally, a dual core processor would be nearly twice as powerful as a single core processor.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] In practice, the performance gain is far smaller, only about 50%, due to imperfect software algorithms and implementation.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Increasing the number of cores in a processor (i.e. dual-core, quad-core, etc.) increases the workload that can be handled.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This means that the processor can now handle numerous asynchronous events, interrupts, etc. which can take a toll on the CPU when overwhelmed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] These cores can be thought of as different floors in a processing plant, with each floor handling a different task.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Sometimes, these cores will handle the same tasks as cores adjacent to them if a single core is not enough to handle the information.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Multi-core CPUs enhance a computer's ability to run several tasks simultaneously by providing additional processing power.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] However, the increase in speed is not directly proportional to the number of cores added.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] This is because the cores need to interact through specific channels, and this inter-core communication consumes a portion of the available processing speed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Due to specific capabilities of modern CPUs, such as simultaneous multithreading and uncore, which involve sharing of actual CPU resources while aiming at increased utilization, monitoring performance levels and hardware use gradually became a more complex task.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] As a response, some CPUs implement additional hardware logic that monitors actual use of various parts of a CPU and provides various counters accessible to software; an example is Intel's *Performance Counter Monitor* technology.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Overclocking is a process of increasing the clock speed of a CPU (and other components) beyond their rated speeds.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Increasing a component's clock rate causes it to perform more operations per second.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Overclocking might increase CPU temperature and cause it to overheat, so most users do not overclock and leave the clock speed unchanged.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/central-processing-unit-p02] Manufacturers may limit the degree to which a component can be overclocked, such as by limiting clock ratios, maximum power consumption, or both.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] The KPTI patches were based on KAISER (short for *Kernel Address Isolation to have Side-channels Efficiently Removed*), a technique conceived in 2016 and published in June 2017 back when Meltdown was not known yet.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] KAISER makes it harder to defeat KASLR, a 2014 mitigation for a much less severe issue.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] In 2014, the Linux kernel adopted kernel address space layout randomization (KASLR), which makes it more difficult to exploit other kernel vulnerabilities, which relies on kernel address mappings remaining hidden from user space.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] Despite prohibiting access to these kernel mappings, it turns out that there are several side-channel attacks in modern processors that can leak the location of this memory, making it possible to work around KASLR.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] KAISER addressed these problems in KASLR by eliminating some sources of address leakage.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] Whereas KASLR merely prevents address mappings from leaking, KAISER also prevents the data from leaking, thereby covering the Meltdown case.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] Without KPTI enabled, whenever executing user-space code (applications), Linux would also keep its entire kernel memory mapped in page tables, although protected from access.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] The advantage is that when the application makes a system call into the kernel or an interrupt is received, kernel page tables are always present, so most context switching-related overheads (TLB flush, page-table swapping, etc.) can be avoided.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] In January 2018, the Meltdown vulnerability was published, known to affect Intel's x86 CPUs and ARM Cortex-A75.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] It was a far more severe vulnerability than the KASLR bypass that KAISER originally intended to fix: It was found that *contents* of kernel memory could also be leaked, not just the locations of memory mappings, as previously thought.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] KPTI (conceptually based on KAISER) prevents Meltdown by preventing most protected locations from being mapped to user space.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] AMD x86 processors are not currently known to be affected by Meltdown and don't need KPTI to mitigate them.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] However, AMD processors are still susceptible to KASLR bypass when KPTI is disabled.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] KPTI fixes these leaks by separating user-space and kernel-space page tables entirely.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] One set of page tables includes both kernel-space and user-space addresses same as before, but it is only used when the system is running in kernel mode.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] The second set of page tables for use in user mode contains a copy of user-space and a minimal set of kernel-space mappings that provides the information needed to enter or exit system calls, interrupts and exceptions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] On processors that support the process-context identifiers (PCID), a translation lookaside buffer (TLB) flush can be avoided, but even then it comes at a significant performance cost, particularly in syscall-heavy and interrupt-heavy workloads.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] Many benchmarks have been done by Phoronix, Redis slowed by 6–7%.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] Linux kernel compilation slowed down by 5% on Haswell.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] KPTI can partially be disabled with the "nopti" kernel boot option.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/kernel-page-table-isolation] Also provisions were created to disable KPTI if newer processors fix the information leaks.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Meltdown affects a wide range of systems.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] At the time of disclosure (2018), this included all devices running any but the most recent and patched versions of iOS, Linux, macOS, or Windows.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Accordingly, many servers and cloud services were impacted, as well as a potential majority of smart devices and embedded devices using ARM-based processors (mobile devices, smart TVs, printers and others), including a wide range of networking equipment.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] A purely software workaround to Meltdown has been assessed as slowing computers between 5 and 30 percent in certain specialized workloads, although companies responsible for software correction of the exploit reported minimal impact from general benchmark testing.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Meltdown was issued a Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures ID of CVE-2017-5754, also known as *Rogue Data Cache Load* (RDCL), in January 2018.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] It was disclosed in conjunction with another exploit, Spectre, with which it shares some characteristics.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The Meltdown and Spectre vulnerabilities are considered "catastrophic" by security analysts.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The vulnerabilities are so severe that security researchers initially believed the reports to be false.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Several procedures to help protect home computers and related devices from the Meltdown and Spectre security vulnerabilities have been published.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Meltdown patches may produce performance loss.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Spectre patches have been reported to significantly reduce performance, especially on older computers; on the then-newest (2017) eighth-generation Core platforms, benchmark performance drops of 2–14 percent have been measured.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] On 18 January 2018, unwanted reboots, even for newer Intel chips, due to Meltdown and Spectre patches, were reported.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] On 15 March 2018, Intel reported that it would redesign its CPUs to help protect against the Meltdown and related Spectre vulnerabilities (especially, Meltdown and Spectre-V2, but not Spectre-V1), and expected to release the newly redesigned processors later in 2018.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] On 8 October 2018, Intel is reported to have added hardware and firmware mitigations regarding Spectre and Meltdown vulnerabilities to its latest processors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Meltdown exploits a race condition, inherent in the design of many modern CPUs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] This occurs between memory access and privilege checking during instruction processing.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Additionally, combined with a cache side-channel attack, this vulnerability allows a process to bypass the normal privilege checks that isolate the exploit process from accessing data belonging to the operating system and other running processes.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The vulnerability allows an unauthorized process to read data from any address that is mapped to the current process's memory space.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Because the affected processors implement instruction pipelining, the data from an unauthorized address will almost always be temporarily loaded into the CPU's cache during out-of-order execution – from which the data can be recovered.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] This can occur even if the original read instruction fails due to privilege checking, or if it never produces a readable result.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Defenses against Meltdown would require avoiding the use of memory mapping in a manner vulnerable to such exploits (i.e. a software-based solution) or avoidance of the underlying race condition (i.e. a modification to the CPUs' microcode or execution path).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The vulnerability is viable on any operating system in which privileged data is mapped into virtual memory for unprivileged processes – which includes many present-day operating systems.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Meltdown could potentially impact a wider range of computers than presently identified, as there is little to no variation in the microprocessor families used by these computers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] A Meltdown attack cannot be detected if it is carried out, as it does not leave any traces in traditional log files.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Meltdown was discovered independently by Jann Horn from Google's Project Zero, Werner Haas and Thomas Prescher from Cyberus Technology, and Daniel Gruss, Moritz Lipp, Stefan Mangard and Michael Schwarz from Graz University of Technology.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The same research teams that discovered Meltdown also discovered Spectre.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The security vulnerability was called Meltdown because "the vulnerability basically melts security boundaries which are normally enforced by the hardware".
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Meltdown relies on a CPU race condition that can arise between instruction execution and privilege checking.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Put briefly, the instruction execution leaves side effects that constitute information not hidden to the process by the privilege check.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The process carrying out Meltdown then uses these side effects to infer the values of memory mapped data, bypassing the privilege check.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The following provides an overview of the exploit, and the memory mapping that is its target.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The attack is described in terms of an Intel processor running Microsoft Windows or Linux, the main test targets used in the original paper, but it also affects other processors and operating systems, including macOS (aka OS X), iOS, and Android.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Modern computer processors use a variety of techniques to gain high levels of efficiency.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Ordinarily, the mechanisms described above are considered secure.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] They provide the basis for most modern operating systems and processors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Meltdown exploits the way these features interact to bypass the CPU's fundamental privilege controls and access privileged and sensitive data from the operating system and other processes.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] To understand Meltdown, consider the data that is mapped in virtual memory (much of which the process is not supposed to be able to access) and how the CPU responds when a process attempts to access unauthorized memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The process is running on a vulnerable version of Windows, Linux, or macOS, on a 64-bit processor of a vulnerable type.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] This is a very common combination across almost all desktop computers, notebooks, laptops, servers and mobile devices.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The CPU encounters an instruction accessing address Base+A, with Base chosen by the attacker.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] This instruction is also scheduled and dispatched to an execution unit.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The privilege check informs the execution unit that the address of the value, A, involved in the access is forbidden to the process (per the information stored by the virtual memory system), and thus the instruction should fail and subsequent instructions should have no effect.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Because these instructions were speculatively executed, however, the data at Base+A may have been cached *before* the privilege check – and may not have been undone by the execution unit (or any other part of the CPU).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] If this is indeed the case, the mere act of caching constitutes a leak of information in and of itself.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The process executes a timing attack by executing instructions referencing memory operands directly.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] To be effective, the operands of these instructions must be at addresses which cover the possible address, Base+A, of the rejected instruction's operand.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Because the data at the address referred to by the rejected instruction, Base+A, was cached nevertheless, an instruction referencing the same address directly will execute faster.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The process can detect this timing difference and determine the address, Base+A, that was calculated for the rejected instruction – and thus determine the value A at the forbidden memory address.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Meltdown uses this technique in sequence to read every address of interest at high speed, and depending on other running processes, the result may contain passwords, encryption data, and any other sensitive information, from any address of any process that exists in its memory map.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] In practice, because cache side-channel attacks are slow, it is faster to extract data one bit at a time (only 2 × 8 = 16 cache attacks needed to read a byte, rather than 256 steps if it tried to read all 8 bits at once).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The impact of Meltdown depends on the design of the CPU, the design of the operating system (specifically how it uses memory paging), and the ability of a malicious party to get any code run on that system, as well as the value of any data it could read if able to execute.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The specific impact depends on the implementation of the address translation mechanism in the OS and the underlying hardware architecture.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The attack can reveal the content of any memory that is mapped into a user address space, even if otherwise protected.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] According to researchers, "every Intel processor that implements out-of-order execution is potentially affected, which is effectively every processor since 1995 (except Intel Itanium, and Intel Atom before 2013)." Intel responded to the reported security vulnerabilities with an official statement.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The vulnerability is expected to impact major cloud providers, such as Amazon Web Services (AWS) and Google Cloud Platform.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Cloud providers allow users to execute programs on the same physical servers where sensitive data might be stored, and rely on safeguards provided by the CPU to prevent unauthorized access to the privileged memory locations where that data is stored, a feature that the Meltdown exploit circumvents.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The original paper reports that paravirtualization (Xen) and containers such as Docker, LXC, and OpenVZ, are affected.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] They report that the attack on a fully virtualized machine allows the guest user space to read from the guest kernel memory, but not read from the host kernel space.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The Meltdown vulnerability primarily affects Intel microprocessors, but the ARM Cortex-A75 and IBM's Power microprocessors are also affected.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The vulnerability does not affect AMD microprocessors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] When the effect of Meltdown was first made public, Intel countered that the flaws affect all processors, but AMD denied this, saying "we believe AMD processors are not susceptible due to our use of privilege level protections within paging architecture".
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Researchers have indicated that the Meltdown vulnerability is exclusive to Intel processors, while the Spectre vulnerability can possibly affect some Intel, AMD, and ARM processors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] However, ARM announced that some of their processors were vulnerable to Meltdown.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Google has reported that any Intel processor since 1995 with out-of-order execution is potentially vulnerable to the Meltdown vulnerability (this excludes Itanium and pre-2013 Intel Atom CPUs).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Intel introduced speculative execution to their processors with Intel's P6 family microarchitecture with the Pentium Pro IA-32 microprocessor in 1995.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] ARM has reported that the majority of their processors are not vulnerable, and published a list of the specific processors that are affected.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The ARM Cortex-A75 core is affected directly by both Meltdown and Spectre vulnerabilities, and Cortex-R7, Cortex-R8, Cortex-A8, Cortex-A9, Cortex-A15, Cortex-A17, Cortex-A57, Cortex-A72, and Cortex-A73 cores are affected only by the Spectre vulnerability.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] This contradicts some early statements made about the Meltdown vulnerability as being Intel-only.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] A large portion of the then-current mid-range Android handsets use the Cortex-A53 or Cortex-A55 in an octa-core arrangement and are not affected by either the Meltdown or Spectre vulnerability as they do not perform out-of-order execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] This includes devices with the Qualcomm Snapdragon 630, Snapdragon 626, Snapdragon 625, and all Snapdragon 4xx processors based on A53 or A55 cores.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Also, no Raspberry Pi computers are vulnerable to either Meltdown or Spectre, except the newly released Raspberry Pi 4, which uses the ARM Cortex-A72 CPU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] IBM has also confirmed that its Power CPUs are affected by both CPU attacks.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Red Hat has publicly announced that the exploits are also for IBM System Z, POWER8, and POWER9 systems.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Oracle has stated that V9-based SPARC systems (T5, M5, M6, S7, M7, M8, M10, M12 processors) are not affected by Meltdown, though older SPARC processors that are no longer supported may be impacted.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Mitigation of the vulnerability requires changes to operating system kernel code, including increased isolation of kernel memory from user-mode processes.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Linux kernel developers have referred to this measure as kernel page-table isolation (KPTI).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] KPTI patches have been developed for Linux kernel 4.15, and have been released as a backport in kernels 4.14.11 and 4.9.75.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Red Hat released kernel updates to their Red Hat Enterprise Linux distributions version 6 and version 7.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] CentOS also already released their kernel updates to CentOS 6 and CentOS 7.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Apple included mitigations in macOS 10.13.2, iOS 11.2, and tvOS 11.2.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] These were released a month before the vulnerabilities were made public.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Apple has stated that watchOS and the Apple Watch are not affected.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Additional mitigations were included in a Safari update as well a supplemental update to macOS 10.13, and iOS 11.2.2.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Microsoft released an emergency update to Windows 10, 8.1, and 7 SP1 to address the vulnerability on 3 January 2018, as well as Windows Server (including Server 2008 R2, Server 2012 R2, and Server 2016) and Windows Embedded Industry.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The update was found to have caused issues on systems running certain AMD CPUs, with some users reporting that their Windows installations did not boot at all after installation.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] On 9 January 2018, Microsoft paused the distribution of the update to systems with affected CPUs while it investigated and addressed this bug.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] It was reported that implementation of KPTI may lead to a reduction in CPU performance, with some researchers claiming up to 30% loss in performance, depending on usage, though Intel considered this to be an exaggeration.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] It was reported that Intel processor generations that support process-context identifiers (PCID), a feature introduced with Westmere and available on all chips from the Haswell architecture onward, were not as susceptible to performance losses under KPTI as older generations that lack it.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] A statement by Intel said that "any performance impacts are workload-dependent, and, for the average computer user, should not be significant and will be mitigated over time".
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] Phoronix benchmarked several popular PC games on a Linux system with Intel's Coffee Lake Core i7-8700K CPU and KPTI patches installed, and found that any performance impact was small to non-existent.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] In other tests, including synthetic I/O benchmarks and databases such as PostgreSQL and Redis, an impact in performance was found, accounting even to tens of percent for some workloads.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] More recently, related tests, involving AMD's FX and Intel's Sandybridge and Ivybridge CPUs, have been reported.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] On 25 January 2018, the current status and possible future considerations in solving the Meltdown and Spectre vulnerabilities were presented.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] In March 2018, Intel announced that it had designed hardware fixes for future processors for Meltdown and Spectre-V2 only, but not Spectre-V1.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] The vulnerabilities were mitigated by a new partitioning system that improves process and privilege-level separation.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/meltdown-security-vulnerability] On 8 October 2018, Intel was reported to have added hardware and firmware mitigations regarding Spectre and Meltdown vulnerabilities to its latest processors.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In computer engineering, **out-of-order execution** (or more formally **dynamic execution**) is an instruction scheduling paradigm used in high-performance central processing units (CPUs) to make use of instruction cycles that would otherwise be wasted.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In this paradigm, a processor executes instructions in an order governed by the availability of input data and execution units, rather than by their original order in a program.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In doing so, the processor can avoid being idle while waiting for the preceding instruction to complete and can, in the meantime, process the next instructions that are able to run immediately and independently.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Out-of-order execution is a restricted form of dataflow architecture, which was a major research area in computer architecture in the 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Arguably the first machine to use out-of-order execution is the CDC 6600 (1964), which used a scoreboard to resolve conflicts.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The 6600 however lacked WAW conflict handling, choosing instead to stall.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] This situation was termed a "First Order Conflict" by Thornton.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Whilst it had both RAW conflict resolution (termed "Second Order Conflict") and WAR conflict resolution (termed "Third Order Conflict") all of which is sufficient to declare it capable of full out-of-order execution, the 6600 did not have precise exception handling.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] An early and limited form of Branch prediction was possible as long as the branch was to locations on what was termed the "Instruction Stack" which was limited to within a depth of seven words from the Program Counter.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] About two years later, the IBM System/360 Model 91 (1966) introduced register renaming with Tomasulo's algorithm, which dissolves false dependencies (WAW and WAR), making full out-of-order execution possible.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In the Model 91 the register renaming is implemented by a bypass termed *Common Data Bus* (CDB) and memory source operand buffers, leaving the physical architectural registers unused for many cycles as the oldest state of registers addressed by any unexecuted instruction is found on the CDB.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Another advantage the Model 91 has over the 6600 is the ability to execute instructions out-of-order in the same execution unit, not just between the units like the 6600.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] This is accomplished by reservation stations, from which instructions go to the execution unit when ready, as opposed to the FIFO queue of each execution unit of the 6600.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The Model 91 is also capable of reordering loads and stores to execute before the preceding loads and stores, unlike the 6600, which only has a limited ability to move loads past loads, and stores past stores, but not loads past stores and stores past loads.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Only the floating-point registers of the Model 91 are renamed, making it subject to the same WAW and WAR limitations as the CDC 6600 when running fixed-point calculations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The 91 and 6600 both also suffer from imprecise exceptions, which needed to be solved before out-of-order execution could be applied generally and made practical outside supercomputers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] To have precise exceptions, the proper in-order state of the program's execution must be available upon an exception.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] By 1985 various approaches were developed as described by James E.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The CDC Cyber 205 was a precursor, as upon a virtual memory interrupt the entire state of the processor (including the information on the partially executed instructions) is saved into an *invisible exchange package*, so that it can resume at the same state of execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] However to make all exceptions precise, there has to be a way to cancel the effects of instructions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The CDC Cyber 990 (1984) implements precise interrupts by using a history buffer, which holds the old (overwritten) values of registers that are restored when an exception necessitates the reverting of instructions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Through simulation, Smith determined that adding a reorder buffer (or history buffer or equivalent) to the Cray-1S would reduce the performance of executing the first 14 Livermore loops (unvectorized) by only 3%.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Important academic research in this subject was led by Yale Patt with his HPSm simulator.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In the 1980s many early RISC microprocessors, had out-of-order writeback to the registers, invariably resulting in imprecise exceptions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The Motorola 88100 was one of the few early microprocessors that did not suffer from imprecise exceptions despite out-of-order writes, although it did allow both precise and imprecise floating-point exceptions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Instructions started execution in order, but some (e.g. floating-point) took more cycles to complete execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] However, the single-cycle execution of the most basic instructions greatly reduced the scope of the problem compared to the CDC 6600.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Smith also researched how to make different execution units operate more independently of each other and of the memory, front-end, and branching.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] He implemented those ideas in the Astronautics ZS-1 (1988), featuring a decoupling of the integer/load/store pipeline from the floating-point pipeline, allowing inter-pipeline reordering.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The ZS-1 was also capable of executing loads ahead of preceding stores.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In his 1984 paper, he opined that enforcing the precise exceptions only on the integer/memory pipeline should be sufficient for many use cases, as it even permits virtual memory.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Each pipeline had an instruction buffer to decouple it from the instruction decoder, to prevent the stalling of the front end.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] To further decouple the memory access from execution, each of the two pipelines was associated with two addressable queues that effectively performed limited register renaming.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] A similar decoupled architecture had been used a bit earlier in the Culler 7.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The ZS-1's ISA, like IBM's subsequent POWER, aided the early execution of branches.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] With the POWER1 (1990), IBM returned to out-of-order execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] It was the first processor to combine register renaming (though again only floating-point registers) with precise exceptions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The reordering capability of even the floating-point instructions is still very limited; due to POWER1's inability to reorder floating-point arithmetic instructions (results became available in-order), their destination registers aren't renamed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] POWER1 also doesn't have reservation stations needed for out-of-order use of the same execution unit.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The next year IBM's ES/9000 model 900 had register renaming added for the general-purpose registers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] It also has reservation stations with six entries for the dual integer unit (each cycle, from the six instructions up to two can be selected and then executed) and six entries for the FPU.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The reordering distance is up to 32 instructions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The A19 of Unisys' A-series of mainframes was also released in 1991 and was claimed to have out-of-order execution, and one analyst called the A19's technology three to five years ahead of the competition.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The first superscalar single-chip processors (Intel i960CA in 1989) used a simple scoreboarding scheduling like the CDC 6600 had a quarter of a century earlier.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In 1992–1996 a rapid advancement of techniques, enabled by increasing transistor counts, saw proliferation down to personal computers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The Motorola 88110 (1992) used a history buffer to revert instructions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Loads could be executed ahead of preceding stores.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] While stores and branches were waiting to start execution, subsequent instructions of other types could keep flowing through all the pipeline stages, including writeback.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The 12-entry capacity of the history buffer placed a limit on the reorder distance.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The PowerPC 601 (1993) was an evolution of the RISC Single Chip, itself a simplification of POWER1.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The 601 permitted branch and floating-point instructions to overtake the integer instructions already in the fetched instruction queue, the lowest four entries of which were scanned for dispatchability.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In the case of a cache miss, loads and stores could be reordered.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Only the link and count registers could be renamed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In the fall of 1994 NexGen and IBM with Motorola brought the renaming of general-purpose registers to single-chip CPUs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] NexGen's Nx586 was the first x86 processor capable of out-of-order execution and featured a reordering distance of up to 14 micro-operations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The PowerPC 603 renamed both the general-purpose and FP registers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Each of the four non-branch execution units can have one instruction wait in front of it without blocking the instruction flow to the other units.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] A five-entry reorder buffer lets no more than four instructions overtake an unexecuted instruction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Due to a store buffer, a load can access cache ahead of a preceding store.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] PowerPC 604 (1995) was the first single-chip processor with execution unit-level reordering, as three out of its six units each had a two-entry reservation station permitting the newer entry to execute before the older.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The reorder buffer capacity is 16 instructions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] A four-entry load queue and a six-entry store queue track the reordering of loads and stores upon cache misses.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Up to 64 instructions can be in a reordered state at a time.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Pentium Pro (1995) introduced a *unified reservation station*, which at the 20 micro-OP capacity permitted very flexible reordering, backed by a 40-entry reorder buffer.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Loads can be reordered ahead of both loads and stores.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The practically attainable per-cycle rate of execution rose further as full out-of-order execution was further adopted by SGI/MIPS (R10000) and HP PA-RISC (PA-8000) in 1996.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The same year Cyrix 6x86 and AMD K5 brought advanced reordering techniques into mainstream personal computers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Since DEC Alpha gained out-of-order execution in 1998 (Alpha 21264), the top-performing out-of-order processor cores have been unmatched by in-order cores other than HP/Intel Itanium 2 and IBM POWER6, though the latter had an out-of-order floating-point unit.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The other high-end in-order processors fell far behind, namely Sun's UltraSPARC III/IV, and IBM's mainframes which had lost the out-of-order execution capability for the second time, remaining in-order into the z10 generation.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Later big in-order processors were focused on multithreaded performance, but eventually the SPARC T series and Xeon Phi changed to out-of-order execution in 2011 and 2016 respectively.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Almost all processors for phones and other lower-end applications remained in-order until c.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] First, Qualcomm's Scorpion (reordering distance of 32) shipped in Snapdragon, and a bit later Arm's A9 succeeded A8.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] For low-end x86 personal computers in-order Bonnell microarchitecture in early Intel Atom processors were first challenged by AMD's Bobcat microarchitecture, and in 2013 were succeeded by an out-of-order Silvermont microarchitecture.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Because the complexity of out-of-order execution precludes achieving the lowest minimum power consumption, cost and size, in-order execution is still prevalent in microcontrollers and embedded systems, as well as in phone-class cores such as Arm's A55 and A510 in big.LITTLE configurations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Out-of-order execution is more sophisticated relative to the baseline of in-order execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In pipelined in-order execution processors, execution of instructions overlap in pipelined fashion with each requiring multiple clock cycles to complete.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The consequence is that results from a previous instruction will lag behind where they may be needed in the next.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In-order execution still has to keep track of these dependencies.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Its approach is however quite unsophisticated: stall, every time.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Out-of-order uses much more sophisticated data tracking techniques, as described below.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] If input operands are available (in processor registers, for instance), the instruction is dispatched to the appropriate functional unit.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] If one or more operands are unavailable during the current clock cycle (generally because they must be fetched from memory), the processor stalls until they are available.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The instruction is executed by the appropriate functional unit.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The functional unit writes the results back to the register file.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Often, an in-order processor has a bit vector recording which registers will be written to by a pipeline.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] If any input operands have the corresponding bit set in this vector, the instruction stalls.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Essentially, the vector performs a greatly simplified role of protecting against register hazards.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Thus out-of-order execution uses 2D matrices whereas in-order execution uses a 1D vector for hazard avoidance.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Instruction dispatch to an instruction queue (also called instruction buffer or reservation stations).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The instruction waits in the queue until its input operands are available.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The instruction can leave the queue before older instructions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The instruction is issued to the appropriate functional unit and executed by that unit.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Only after all older instructions have their results written back to the register file, then this result is written back to the register file.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] This is called the graduation or retire stage.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The key concept of out-of-order processing is to allow the processor to avoid a class of stalls that occur when the data needed to perform an operation are unavailable.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In the outline above, the processor avoids the stall that occurs in step 2 of the in-order processor when the instruction is not completely ready to be processed due to missing data.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The way the instructions are ordered in the original computer code is known as *program order*, in the processor they are handled in *data order*, the order in which the data becomes available in the processor's registers.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Fairly complex circuitry is needed to convert from one ordering to the other and maintain a logical ordering of the output.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The benefit of out-of-order processing grows as the instruction pipeline deepens and the speed difference between main memory (or cache memory) and the processor widens.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] On modern machines, the processor runs many times faster than the memory, so during the time an in-order processor spends waiting for data to arrive, it could have theoretically processed a large number of instructions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] One of the differences created by the new paradigm is the creation of queues that allow the dispatch step to be decoupled from the issue step and the graduation stage to be decoupled from the execute stage.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] An early name for the paradigm was *decoupled architecture*.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In the earlier *in-order* processors, these stages operated in a fairly lock-step, pipelined fashion.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The fetch and decode stages is separated from the execute stage in a pipelined processor by using a buffer.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The buffer's purpose is to partition the memory access and execute functions in a computer program and achieve high performance by exploiting the fine-grain parallelism between the two.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] In doing so, it effectively hides all memory latency from the processor's perspective.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] A larger buffer can, in theory, increase throughput.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] However, if the processor has a branch misprediction then the entire buffer may need to be flushed, wasting a lot of clock cycles and reducing the effectiveness.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Furthermore, larger buffers create more heat and use more die space.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] For this reason processor designers today favor a multi-threaded design approach.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Decoupled architectures are generally thought of as not useful for general-purpose computing as they do not handle control-intensive code well.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Control intensive code include such things as nested branches that occur frequently in operating system kernels.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Decoupled architectures play an important role in scheduling in very long instruction word (VLIW) architectures.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The queue for results is necessary to resolve issues such as branch mispredictions and exceptions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The results queue allows programs to be restarted after an exception and for the instructions to be completed in program order.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The queue allows results to be discarded due to mispredictions on older branch instructions and exceptions taken on older instructions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] The ability to issue instructions past branches that have yet to be resolved is known as speculative execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Are the instructions dispatched to a centralized queue or to multiple distributed queues?
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] processors use queues that are distributed among the different functional units while other out-of-order processors use a centralized queue.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] Is there an actual results queue or are the results written directly into a register file?
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] For the latter, the queueing function is handled by register maps that hold the register renaming information for each instruction in flight.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/out-of-order-execution] while most later out-of-order processors use register maps.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] The objective is to provide more concurrency if extra resources are available.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] This approach is employed in a variety of areas, including branch prediction in pipelined processors, value prediction for exploiting value locality, prefetching memory and files, and optimistic concurrency control in database systems.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] Speculative multithreading is a special case of speculative execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] Modern pipelined microprocessors use speculative execution to reduce the cost of conditional branch instructions using schemes that predict the execution path of a program based on the history of branch executions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] In order to improve performance and utilization of computer resources, instructions can be scheduled at a time when it has not yet been determined that the instructions will need to be executed, ahead of a branch.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] Eager execution is a form of speculative execution where both sides of the conditional branch are executed; however, the results are committed only if the predicate is true.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] With unlimited resources, eager execution (also known as *oracle execution*) would in theory provide the same performance as perfect branch prediction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] With limited resources, eager execution should be employed carefully, since the number of resources needed grows exponentially with each level of branch executed eagerly.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] Predictive execution is a form of speculative execution where some outcome is predicted and execution proceeds along the predicted path until the actual result is known.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] If the prediction is true, the predicted execution is allowed to commit; however, if there is a misprediction, execution has to be unrolled and re-executed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] Common forms of this include branch predictors and memory dependence prediction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] A generalized form is sometimes referred to as value prediction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] In computer science and processor design, runahead is a technique that allows a computer processor to speculatively pre-process instructions during cache miss cycles.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] The pre-processed instructions are used to generate instruction and data stream prefetches by executing instructions leading to cache misses (typically called *long latency loads*) before they would normally occur, effectively hiding memory latency.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] In runahead, the processor uses the idle execution resources to calculate instruction and data stream addresses using the available information that is independent of a cache miss.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] Once the processor has resolved the initial cache miss, all runahead results are discarded, and the processor resumes execution as normal.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] The primary use case of the technique is to mitigate the effects of the memory wall.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] The technique may also be used for other purposes, such as pre-computing branch outcomes to achieve highly accurate branch prediction.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] Lazy execution is the opposite of eager execution, and does not involve speculation.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] The incorporation of speculative execution into implementations of the Haskell programming language, a lazy language, is a current research topic.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] Eager Haskell, a variant of the language, is designed around the idea of speculative execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] A 2003 PhD thesis made GHC support a kind of speculative execution with an abortion mechanism to back out in case of a bad choice called *optimistic execution*.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/speculative-execution] Starting in 2017, a series of security vulnerabilities were found in the implementations of speculative execution on common processor architectures which effectively enabled an elevation of privileges.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Modern computers are highly parallel devices, composed of components with very different performance characteristics.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] The prediction may be based on recent behavior of the system.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] When the earlier, slower operation completes, the microprocessor determines whether the prediction was correct or incorrect.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] If it was correct then execution proceeds uninterrupted; if it was incorrect then the microprocessor rolls back the speculatively executed operations and repeats the original instruction with the real result of the slow operation.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Specifically, a *transient instruction* refers to an instruction processed by error by the processor (incriminating the branch predictor in the case of Spectre) which can affect the micro-architectural state of the processor, leaving the architectural state without any trace of its execution.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In terms of the directly visible behavior of the computer it is as if the speculatively executed code "never happened".
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] However, this speculative execution may affect the state of certain components of the microprocessor, such as the cache, and this effect may be discovered by careful monitoring of the timing of subsequent operations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In early January 2018, it was reported that all Intel processors made since 1995 (besides Intel Itanium and pre-2013 Intel Atom) have been subject to two security flaws dubbed **Meltdown** and **Spectre**.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] The impact on performance resulting from software patches is "workload-dependent".
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Several procedures to help protect home computers and related devices from the Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities have been published.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Spectre patches have been reported to significantly slow down performance, especially on older computers; on the newer 8th-generation Core platforms, benchmark performance drops of 2–14% have been measured.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Meltdown patches may also produce performance loss.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] It is believed that "hundreds of millions" of systems could be affected by these flaws.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] More security flaws were disclosed on May 3, 2018, on August 14, 2018, on January 18, 2019, and on March 5, 2020.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] At the time, Intel was not commenting on this issue.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] On March 15, 2018, Intel reported that it will redesign its CPUs (performance losses to be determined) to protect against the Spectre security vulnerability, and expects to release the newly redesigned processors later in 2018.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] On May 3, 2018, eight additional Spectre-class flaws were reported.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Intel reported that they are preparing new patches to mitigate these flaws.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] On August 14, 2018, Intel disclosed three additional chip flaws referred to as **L1 Terminal Fault (L1TF)**.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] They reported that previously released microcode updates, along with new, pre-release microcode updates can be used to mitigate these flaws.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Coffee Lake-series CPUs are even more vulnerable, due to hardware mitigations for Spectre.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] On March 5, 2020, computer security experts reported another Intel chip security flaw, besides the Meltdown and Spectre flaws, with the systematic name CVE-2019-0090 (or "**Intel CSME Bug**").
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] This newly found flaw is not fixable with a firmware update, and affects nearly "all Intel chips released in the past five years".
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In March 2021 AMD security researchers discovered that the Predictive Store Forwarding algorithm in Zen 3 CPUs could be used by malicious applications to access data it shouldn't be accessing.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] According to Phoronix there's little performance impact in disabling the feature.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In June 2021, two new vulnerabilities, **Speculative Code Store Bypass** (**SCSB**, CVE-2021-0086) and **Floating Point Value Injection** (FPVI, CVE-2021-0089), affecting *all* modern x86-64 CPUs both from Intel and AMD were discovered.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In order to mitigate them software has to be rewritten and recompiled.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] ARM CPUs are not affected by SCSB but some certain ARM architectures are affected by FPVI.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Also in June 2021, MIT researchers revealed the **PACMAN** attack on Pointer Authentication Codes (PAC) in ARM v8.3A.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In August 2021 a vulnerability called "**Transient Execution of Non-canonical Accesses**" affecting certain AMD CPUs was disclosed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] It requires the same mitigations as the MDS vulnerability affecting certain Intel CPUs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Since most x86 software is already patched against MDS and this vulnerability has the exact same mitigations, software vendors don't have to address this vulnerability.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In October 2021 for the first time ever a vulnerability similar to Meltdown was disclosed to be affecting all AMD CPUs however the company doesn't think any new mitigations have to be applied and the existing ones are already sufficient.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In March 2022, a new variant of the Spectre vulnerability called **Branch History Injection** was disclosed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] It affects certain ARM64 CPUs and the following Intel CPU families: Cascade Lake, Ice Lake, Tiger Lake and Alder Lake.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] According to Linux kernel developers AMD CPUs are also affected.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In March 2022, a vulnerability affecting a wide range of AMD CPUs was disclosed under CVE-2021-26341.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In June 2022, multiple MMIO Intel CPUs vulnerabilities related to execution in virtual environments were announced.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In July 2022, the **Retbleed** vulnerability was disclosed affecting Intel Core 6 to 8th generation CPUs and AMD Zen 1, 1+ and 2 generation CPUs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Newer Intel microarchitectures as well as AMD starting with Zen 3 are not affected.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] The mitigations for the vulnerability decrease the performance of the affected Intel CPUs by up to 39%, while AMD CPUs lose up to 14%.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In August 2022, the **SQUIP** vulnerability was disclosed affecting Ryzen 2000–5000 series CPUs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] According to AMD the existing mitigations are enough to protect from it.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] According to a Phoronix review released in October, 2022 Zen 4/Ryzen 7000 CPUs are not slowed down by mitigations, in fact disabling them leads to a performance loss.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In February 2023 a vulnerability affecting a wide range of AMD CPU architectures called "**Cross-Thread Return Address Predictions**" was disclosed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In July 2023 a critical vulnerability in the Zen 2 AMD microarchitecture called **Zenbleed** was made public.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] AMD released a microcode update to fix it.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In August 2023 a vulnerability in AMD's Zen 1, Zen 2, Zen 3, and Zen 4 microarchitectures called **Inception** was revealed and assigned CVE-2023-20569.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] According to AMD it is not practical but the company released a microcode update for the affected products.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Also in August 2023 a new vulnerability called **Downfall** or **Gather Data Sampling** was disclosed, affecting Intel CPU Skylake, Cascade Lake, Cooper Lake, Ice Lake, Tiger Lake, Amber Lake, Kaby Lake, Coffee Lake, Whiskey Lake, Comet Lake & Rocket Lake CPU families.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Intel will release a microcode update for affected products.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] The **SLAM** vulnerability (**Spectre based on Linear Address Masking**) reported in 2023 neither has received a corresponding CVE, nor has been confirmed or mitigated against.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In March 2024, a variant of Spectre-V1 attack called **GhostRace** was published.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] It was claimed it affected all the major microarchitectures and vendors, including Intel, AMD and ARM.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] AMD dismissed the vulnerability (calling it "Speculative Race Conditions (SRCs)") claiming that existing mitigations were enough.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Linux kernel developers chose not to add mitigations citing performance concerns.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] The Xen hypervisor project released patches to mitigate the vulnerability but they are not enabled by default.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Also in March 2024, a vulnerability in Intel Atom processors called **Register File Data Sampling** (**RFDS**) was revealed.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Its mitigations incur a slight performance degradation.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In April 2024, it was revealed that the BHI vulnerability in certain Intel CPU families could be still exploited in Linux entirely in user space without using any kernel features or root access despite existing mitigations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Intel recommended "additional software hardening".
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In June 2024, Samsung Research and Seoul National University researchers revealed the **TikTag** attack against the Memory Tagging Extension in ARM v8.5A CPUs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] The researchers created PoCs for Google Chrome and the Linux kernel.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Researchers from VUSec previously revealed ARM's Memory Tagging Extension is vulnerable to speculative probing.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In July 2024, UC San Diego researchers revealed the **Indirector** attack against Intel Alder Lake and Raptor Lake CPUs leveraging high-precision Branch Target Injection (BTI).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Intel downplayed the severity of the vulnerability and claimed the existing mitigations are enough to tackle the issue.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In January 2025, Georgia Institute of Technology researchers published two whitepapers on **Data Speculation Attacks via Load Address Prediction on Apple Silicon (SLAP)** and Breaking the Apple M3 CPU via False Load Output Predictions (FLOP).
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Also in January 2025, ARM disclosed a vulnerability (CVE-2024-7881) in which an unprivileged context can trigger a data memory-dependent prefetch engine to fetch data from a privileged location, potentially leading to unauthorized access.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] To mitigate the issue, Arm recommends disabling the affected prefetcher by setting CPUACTLR6_EL1[41].
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In May 2025, VUSec released three vulnerabilities extending on Spectre-v2 in various Intel and ARM architectures under the moniker **Training Solo**.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Mitigations require a microcode update for Intel CPUs and changes in the Linux kernel.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Also in May 2025, ETH Zurich Computer Security Group "COMSEC" disclosed the **Branch Privilege Injection** vulnerability affecting all Intel x86 architectures starting from the 9th generation (Coffee Lake Refresh) under CVE-2024-45332.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] A microcode update is required to mitigate it.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] It comes with a performance cost up to 8%.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In July 2025, AMD disclosed a new class of speculative execution vulnerabilities known as **Transient Scheduler Attacks (TSA)**, which were discovered by researchers from Microsoft.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] The attacks are affecting AMD Zen 3 and Zen 4 microarchitectures, and they exploit microarchitectural timing leaks in CPU scheduler logic—specifically, the forwarding of incorrect data during false completion of speculative loads—to infer sensitive data from other processes or privilege levels.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] TSA encompasses four vulnerabilities: CVE-2024-36350 (TSA-SQ), which leaks data from prior stores; CVE-2024-36357 (TSA-L1), which leverages the L1 data cache; CVE-2024-36348, enabling speculative reads of control registers; and CVE-2024-36349, which leaks TSC_AUX register values.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Mitigations include microcode updates, Linux kernel patches (`tsa=` tunable), and optional use of the `VERW` instruction—albeit with potential performance costs.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] The flaw affects AMD Zen 1–5 and Intel “Coffee Lake” processors, and mitigations include Linux kernel patches that conditionally issue Indirect Branch Prediction Barrier (IBPB) instructions on VMEXITs before returning control to user-space in order to flush predictor state.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] The researchers demonstrated that even relatively "simple" in-order RISC-V cores can leak sensitive information through timing channels, unprivileged performance counters, and undocumented vendor-specific extensions.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] The authors argued that manual analysis of such designs does not scale and presented **RISCover**, an open-source differential fuzzing framework, to compare architectural behavior across cores and configurations.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] In April 2026, Floating Point Divider State Sampling (FP-DSS), a transient execution vulnerability, affecting multiple generations of AMD CPUs, was reported in a paper titled "TREVEX: A Black-Box Detection Framework For Data-Flow Transient Execution Vulnerabilities".
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Spectre class vulnerabilities will remain unfixed because otherwise CPU designers will have to disable speculative execution which will entail a massive performance loss.
[src:meltdown-mitigation/transient-execution-cpu-vulnerability] Despite this, AMD has managed to design Zen 4 such a way its performance is *not* affected by mitigations.
